text:
Four years ago, China revised its  Law on the Protection of Minors,  limiting the visibility of online content deemed potentially harmful to children, and directing regulators to clarify the scope of that broad category at a later stage. These rules are important beyond the stated goal of child-protection, because barring such content from prominent spaces, such as website homepages and lists of trending topics, inevitably reduces adults’ exposure to it as well. What’s worse, the threat of steep penalties for violations gives platforms strong incentives to err on the side of caution by pushing ever more information to the sidelines.
Earlier this year, long-anticipated clarification finally came into sight with the release of draft guidance for identifying this potentially harmful content. Unfortunately, the new authority does little to resolve the uncertainty. The draft remains vague, internally inconsistent, and misaligned with the existing law; creating as many problems as it solves.
Background:
The new draft  Measures for Categorizing Online Information that Might Impact Minors’ Physical and Psychological Health   can only be understood in the context of China’s broader information controls.
China’s general online  content control regime  focuses on three broad groups of content: encouraged ‘ positive content’ , prohibited  ‘illegal content’ , and discouraged ‘ negative content’ . [see table 1 below]
It is a punishable offense to create, reproduce, or transmit “illegal content”, such as information promoting terrorism, attacking the national leadership, or leaking state secrets. The broader category of “negative content” is generally permissible, but platforms can still be punished for actively promoting it by placing it in certain key locations. Those high-visibility areas should instead be filled with neutral, or ideally, “encouraged” positive-energy content.
