Content for Minors
The revised  Law on the Protection of Minors (LPM) and subsequent  Regulations on the Protection of Minors Online   (RPMO) addressed two additional categories of content: (1) Content harmful to minors, and (2) content that “might impact minors’ physical or psychological health.”
The first category, content harmful to minors, includes prohibited “illegal content” from the broader regulatory scheme, as well as content promoting self-harm, and is thus largely prohibited for minors and adults alike.
Online platforms, game designers, users, and parents have special obligations to help minors avoid the second category of information, which is referred to here as “potentially harmful to minors” (PHM) content. The obligations primarily include:
[No Targeting Minors]  This content must never appear in online products and services that are specifically for minors, and must not be sent directly to minors [LPM 80, RPMO 24, 25]
[Labeling Requirement]  Where such content does appear in services or products, it must be clearly labeled as potentially harmful to minors, and platforms are responsible for ensuring that users also appropriately label their content. [LPM 51, RPMP 23, Draft article 9]
[No Promotion]  Like “negative content” in the general content regulation scheme, PHM content must never appear in eye-catching positions, such as home pages, pop-up windows, or trending topic lists. [RPMO 24]
As mentioned above, the LPM left defining the specific scope of PHM content to future regulations. The  Regulations on the Protection of Minors Online  only added that PHM information includes content that might lead minors to imitate unsafe behaviors or violate social mores, or that could cause extreme feelings, or lead to bad habits. This description was also included in recent guidelines on “ minors’ modes for mobile internet ,” and with the exception of ‘extreme feelings’ reflects “negative content” items under the broader content regulations.
Terms like “unsafe behaviors”, “violating social mores”, “extreme feelings”, and “bad habits” read like a wish list of stereotypical adolescent traits the regulators might hope to curb, but are too vague to serve as workable standards for content regulation.
The New Draft
The Draft Measures are the long-overdue response to the Law on the Protection of Minors’ call, made four years earlier, for the cybersecurity authorities to work with other departments to determine the types and scope of PHM content. Unfortunately, they fail to deliver the promised clarity.
The Measures begin with a definition of PHM content in Article 2 that essentially recites the categories of PHM previously raised by the Regulations on the Protection of Minors Online. When the Measures continue by providing detailed illustrative lists of individual types of PHM content in articles 3-7, however, they don’t closely follow that definition.
Table 2: Categories of PHM content in the Definition, versus the categories further elaborated on in subsequent articles.
The first two categories, information causing minors to imitate negative conduct or impacting minors’ values, loosely correspond to the Measure’s definition of PHM. Content encouraging imitation of  unsafe  conduct or causing extreme feelings is folded into the first category as examples of ‘negative conduct’, as are more specific bad habits, such as smoking, drinking, and celebrity worship. The following three categories, however, go in a very different direction, discussing information using minors’ images, disclosing minors’ personal information, or leading to internet addiction, and this shift creates a few problems.
The first issue is likely just the result of sloppy drafting. Not including the three new categories in the formal definition of PHM content creates a basic disconnect: the subsequent lists elaborating on those categories can’t help clarify the definition if they illustrate terms that aren’t even a part of that definition at all.
The second issue is a more fundamental conceptual disconnect. The potential harm in PHM content comes from minors’ exposure to certain information. Accordingly, the rules for handling PHM content are all aimed at helping minors avoid that harmful content, such as by clearly labeling it and removing it from prominent positions and recommendations. The definitions’ categories of PHM are identified solely by the negative effects they may have on minors, such as leading them to imitate bad conduct or triggering extreme emotional responses.
The new categories, however, don’t follow this logic. Instead, they discuss information which may be harmful to minors in other ways, such as in its production (as in short videos pranking or mocking minors) or from other people’s access to and abuse of the information (as in leaks of personal information). Labeling such information as harmful to minors and limiting minors’ exposure to this information won’t prevent the harm involved.
China has separate legal authority aimed expressly at protecting minors’ personal information, fighting internet addiction, and stopping the online financial and sexual exploitation of minors. These issues are further addressed in the comprehensive  Regulations on the Protection of Minors Online .  Including them as PHM isn’t helpful.
In addition to these new problems, the original problem of the rules being unworkably vague remains. How should a platform or user identify, for example, content that might “entice minors to make bad/undesirable friends” [不良交友的].  Consider Table 3’s summary of each category in the draft.
